{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17514660","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17514660"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T13:25:01+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T13:25:01+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12350"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"12350","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/12350"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.06,0.78,0.01,0.08,0.07]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4871"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"78599"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"4871","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/4871"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12350"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"63941"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"4"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1307"},{"type":"tags","id":"2436"},{"type":"tags","id":"3576"},{"type":"tags","id":"4173"},{"type":"tags","id":"4962"},{"type":"tags","id":"4980"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"4988"},{"type":"tags","id":"4992"},{"type":"tags","id":"10948"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11634"},{"type":"tags","id":"11640"},{"type":"tags","id":"11642"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"},{"type":"tags","id":"11691"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"7861"},{"type":"contributions","id":"9499"},{"type":"contributions","id":"26732"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42743"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"78599","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/78599"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 34-year-old woman presents to a fertility clinic after unsuccessfully trying to conceive for the past two years. She is disheartened by her inability to get pregnant. She also experiences heavy menstrual bleeding that hinders her ability to work and requires her to be at home. She keeps the heater on at home due to feeling cold. She feels depressed due to significant weight gain and fears not being loved by anyone. On examination, she appears tired, with puffy eyes and thinning hair. Her pulse is 56/min, blood pressure is 125/82 mmHg and temperature is 36\u00b0C.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Graves disease","Hashimoto\u2019s thyroiditis","Non-toxic goitre","Panhypopituitarism","Polycystic ovarian syndrome"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHashimoto\u0027s thyroiditis\u003C/strong\u003E is an autoimmune condition characterized by inflammation of the thyroid gland, resulting in its destruction over time. This leads to decreased production of thyroid hormones, causing hypothyroidism. The symptoms described in the case, such as heavy menstrual bleeding, fatigue, hair thinning, weight gain, intolerance to cold, and bradycardia, are all commonly associated with hypothyroidism. In Hashimoto\u0027s thyroiditis, you would expect to find elevated levels of thyroid peroxidase antibodies and thyroglobulin antibodies.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EGraves disease\u003C/strong\u003E is an autoimmune disorder in which the immune system mistakenly stimulates the thyroid gland to produce excessive amounts of thyroid hormones. This leads to hyperthyroidism, which can cause symptoms such as weight loss, increased appetite, anxiety, irritability, heat intolerance, tremors, and tachycardia. The patient in the case, however, presents with symptoms consistent with hypothyroidism rather than hyperthyroidism, making Graves disease less likely. In Graves\u0027 disease, you would expect to find elevated levels of thyroid-stimulating immunoglobulins and TSH receptor antibodies.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ENon-toxic goitre\u003C/strong\u003E refers to an enlarged thyroid gland that is not associated with hyperthyroidism or hypothyroidism. Non-toxic goitre does not explain this patient\u0027s heavy menstrual bleeding, fatigue, hair thinning, weight gain, intolerance to cold, and bradycardia, and so it is incorrect.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPanhypopituitarism\u003C/strong\u003E is a rare condition characterized by the deficiency of multiple hormones produced by the pituitary gland. It can occur due to various causes, including tumours, trauma, infections, or autoimmune conditions. The symptoms can include fatigue, infertility, menstrual irregularities, and intolerance to stress or cold. While this patient has some symptoms that could be associated with pituitary hormonal imbalances, such as infertility and menstrual irregularities, the other symptoms and findings described are more consistent with primary thyroid dysfunction rather than a pituitary gland disorder.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPolycystic Ovarian Syndrome (PCOS)\u003C/strong\u003E is a hormonal disorder that affects women of reproductive age. It is characterized by multiple cysts on the ovaries, irregular or absent menstrual periods, infertility, weight gain, hirsutism and acne. This patient has heavy menstrual bleeding (rather than oligomenorrhoea) and hair thinning (not hirsutism) and so this makes this diagnosis less likely.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Hashimoto\u0027s thyroiditis is an autoimmune condition characterized by inflammation of the thyroid gland, resulting in its destruction over time.","Hypothyroidism can present with symptoms such as weight gain, fatigue, cold intolerance, and menstrual irregularities.","Elevated levels of thyroid peroxidase antibodies and thyroglobulin antibodies are indicative of Hashimoto\u0027s thyroiditis."],"references":["Mincer DL, Jialal I. Hashimoto Thyroiditis. [Updated 2022 Jun 21]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2022 Jan-. Available from: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/29083758/","Akamizu T, Amino N. Hashimoto\u2019s Thyroiditis. [Updated 2017 Jul 17]. In: Feingold KR, Anawalt B, Blackman MR, et al., editors. Endotext [Internet]. South Dartmouth (MA): MDText.com, Inc.; 2000-. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK285557/","Klubo-Gwiezdzinska J, Wartofsky L. Hashimoto thyroiditis: an evidence-based guide to etiology, diagnosis and treatment. Pol Arch Intern Med. 2022 Mar 30;132(3):16222. doi: 10.20452/pamw.16222. Epub 2022 Mar 3. PMID: 35243857; PMCID: PMC9478900. Available from: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/35243857/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"63941"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12350"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"63941","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/63941"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-11T18:09:37+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-11T18:10:28+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4871"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"78599"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"4","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/4"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83c\udf6c","name":"Endocrinology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:43+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"25","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/25"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc68\u